A free preprint server for the Earth Sciences
What is a preprint & preprint server?

A preprint is a version of a scholarly paper that precedes publication in a peer-reviewed journal. EarthArXiv is a platform built to host preprints in many subject areas, such as Earth Sciences, Environmental Sciences, Oceanography and Athmospheric Sciences and Meteorology, Engineering, Computer Sciences, Library and Information Science, ...
Supporters
Are you crazy, and does this really work?
No. And yes. EarthArXiv was launched in October 2017 and received 400 submissions in the first 8 months.
https://eartharxiv.github.io/blogs/2018_06_narock/
#OpenScience
#OpenAccess
Why should I consider submitting a preprint?

Rapid dissemination of research: Preprints are citable and shareable immediately after submission. Data suggest that preprints subsequently published in a formal journal are cited more quickly. OSF preprints are indexed by Google Scholar! No paywalls!

Citations: Preprints can help early career researchers build a scholarly track record! This can benefit people seeking funding or a job. An increasing number of funding agencies and universities now allow preprint citations in support of grant proposals and job applications.
Engagement: Making your work open and freely available allows anyone in the world to discover your work without delay and give feedback.
Research is more than text: Publish large datasets (OSF: up to 5GB per file) alongside the preprint text and link external repositories (GitHub, Dropbox, ...).
There is evidence that submissions to preprint servers such as arXiv.org attract citations earlier and have a higher cumulative number of citations, see https://arxiv.org/abs/0906.5418
Will someone steal my work in my preprint?

There is no evidence that preprints lead to being scooped. All preprints are minted with a unique DOI upon submission, helping establish priority. Preprint and peer reviewed article are published as distinct works.
Will publishing a preprint mean I cant publish in a journal?
In most cases, no. Many publishers have preprint-friendly policies for their journals. Check policies at www.sherpa.ac.uk/romeo/
The OSF supports anonymous read-only links for blind peer-review.
Why publish a paper if the work is already a preprint?

Formal journal publications still influence funding and promotions; the vast majority of research-paper preprints are therefore also submitted to journals. Upon acceptance you can update your preprint to direct readers to the peer reviewed article.
Can EarthArXiv only host preprints?

No. EarthArXiv also hosts postprints (i.e. the Author Accepted Manuscript, an accepted version of paper, before typesetting, or the Version of Record, the published version of a paper, after typesetting). Suitable manuscripts are research articles, review papers, case studies, technical notes, dataset description papers, confirmatory studies, "null results". But (for now) also no posters, commentaries, theses, talks, software articles, or abstracts.
http://www.prepubmed.org/monthly_stats/
